<div class="right-content" style="border: 1px solid rgb(224, 224, 224); background: rgb(249, 249, 249) none repeat scroll 0% 50%; -moz-background-clip: -moz-initial; -moz-background-origin: -moz-initial; -moz-background-inline-policy: -moz-initial; width: 580px; margin-bottom: 10px;">
<table style="text-align: left; width: 566px;" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; width: 119px;">Catalog Description<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; font-family: Bitstream Charter;">Introduction
to
the design and
implementation of programming languages: linguistic features for
expressing algorithms; formal syntax specification; introduction to
language semantics and parsing; declarative programming (functional and
goal-driven); scripting languages; imperative programming (procedural
and object-oriented); comparative design and implementation issues
across languages and paradigms. Assignments emphasize languages such as
Prolog, Haskell, Python, and Ruby. <br>
Required Lab includes student
presentations.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">Prerequisites</td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><span style="font-family: Bitstream Charter;">CS 375 and 373</span> </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; width: 119px;">Goals<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; font-family: Bitstream Charter;">Develop
computer
science professionals who are knowledgeable consumers of programming
languages, able to understand the strengths and limitations of
languages and why the languages have them. <br>
      <ul>
        <li>Have a firm grasp of different language features included
in common languages such as C, C++,C#, Java, Haskell, Prolog and
scripting
languages; understand the benefits and drawbacks of these features.</li>
        <li>Have a clear understanding of the different language
paradigms, their benefits and drawbacks. Understand and appreciate the
distinctions between imperative versus declarative languages;
functional versus logic versus object-oriented languages.</li>
        <li>Understand how various language features are implemented,
with a view to better understand design choices and trade-offs in a
language, and most importantly, become more effective programmers
whatever language you choose to program in.</li>
        <li>Acquire a good working knowledge of different programming
styles and develop discipline in programming. Understand and use modern
language features such as abstract data types, type-safe programming,
inheritance, higher-order functions, etc.</li>
      </ul>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; width: 119px;"><span style="font-family: Bitstream Charter;">T</span>extbook<br>
Required<br>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; width: 459px; font-family: Bitstream Charter;"><a href="http://ftp.cs.rochester.edu/%7Escott/pragmatics/"><u><i>Programming
Language Pragmatics</i></u></a>, 3nd Edition, <a href="http://www.cs.rochester.edu/%7Escott/">Michael L. Scott</a>, <a href="http://www.mkp.com/">Morgan
Kaufmann Publishers</a>, 2009 - <a href="http://ftp.cs.rochester.edu/u/scott/pragmatics/2e/errata.shtml=">Errata</a><span style="font-weight: bold;"></span><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td style="vertical-align: top; width: 119px;">Recommended<br>
